s Press|isbn= 9781888363371}} \n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mR2hBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA70|title= The Boxing Filmography: American Features, 1920-2003|first=Frederick V.|last=Romano|year=2004|publisher=McFarland|isbn= 9780786417933}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a4qhCAAAQBAJ&pg=PA39|title=A Moon for the Misbegotten on the American Stage: A History of the Major Productions|first=Laura|last=Shea|year=2015|publisher=McFarland|isbn=9781476621777}}\n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nKz0AAAAMAAJ&dq=james+dunn|title=That's Dancing!|first=Tony|last=Thomas|year=1984|publisher=Abrams}} \n*{{cite book|ref=harv|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kCjT3AvbN5QC&pg=PA80|title=Lost Laughs of '50s and '60s Television: Thirty Sitcoms That Faded Off Screen|first=David C.|last=Tucker|year=2010|publisher=McFarland|isbn= 9780786455829}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Portal|Biography|New York (state)|Film|Television|Theater}}\n* {{IMDb name|id=0007223|name=James Dunn}}\n* {{IBDB name}}\n* {{Find a Grave|10397211}}\n* [http://www.virtual-history.com/movie/person/7943/james-dunn James Dunn] at Virtual History\n* [http://jamesdunnfans.wordpress.com Remembering Jimmy: The Life and Films of James Dunn (fan site)]\n\n{{Commons category|James Dunn}}\n{{AcademyAwardBestSupportingActor 1941-1960}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dunn, James}}\n[[Category:1901 births]]\n[[Category:1967 deaths]]\n[[Category:American male film actors]]\n[[Category:American male television actors]]\n[[Category:American male stage actors]]\n[[Category:Vaudeville performers]]\n[[Category:Male actors from New York City]]\n[[Category:20th Century Fox contract players]]\n[[Category:20th-century American male actors]]\n[[Category:Best Supporting Actor Academy Award winners]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American actor}}\n\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = James Dunn\n| image       = James Dunn pg1036.jpg\n|caption      = Dunn in 1936\n| birth_name  = James Howard Dunn\n| birth_date  = {{birth date|1901|11|02}}\n| birth_place = [[Manhattan]], New York, U.S.\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|1967|09|01|1901|11|02}}\n| death_place = [[Santa Monica, California]]\n| occupation  = [[Actor]]\n| spouse      = Unknown (m. 19??; d. 1922) <br />[[Frances Gifford]] (m. 1938; d. 1943)<br />Edna Rush (m. 1945; his death 1967)\n| yearsactive = 1927\u20131966\n}}\n'''James Howard Dunn''' (November 2, 1901 \u2013 September 1, 1967), billed as '''Jimmy Dunn''' in his early career,<ref name=dispatch>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48352743/st-louis-post-dispatch/|title=On Making the Movie Stars|newspaper=[[St. Louis Post-Dispatch]]|date=January 29, 1933|page=20|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> was an American stage, film, and television actor. The son of a New York stockbroker, he initially worked in his father's firm but was more interested in theater. He landed jobs as an extra in [[short films]] produced by [[Paramount Pictures]] in its Long Island studio, and also performed with several stock theater companies, culminating with playing the male lead in ''[[Sweet Adeline (musical)|Sweet Adeline]]'' on [[Broadway theatre|Broadway]]. This performance attracted the attention of film studio executives, and in 1931, [[Fox Film]] signed him to a Hollywood contract. \n\nHis screen debut in the 1931 film ''[[Bad Girl (1931 film)|Bad Girl]]'' made him an overnight box-office star and he was cast as the lead in a succession of romantic drama and comedy films. In 1934, he co-starred with [[Shirley Temple]] in her first three films. In 1935, at the height of his popularity, he broke his studio contract two years before it expired and became a free agent. With musicals on the wane in the late 1930s, he was cast in a series of [[B movie]]s and began struggling with alcoholism in his personal life. In 1945, having not worked in film for five years, he was selected by director [[Elia Kazan]] for the role of Johnny Nolan, the dreamy alcoholic father in ''[[A Tree Grows in Brooklyn (1945 film)|A Tree Grows in Brooklyn]]'' (1945), which earned him the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]]. \n\nThe Oscar did not advance his film career, however, and while he still found roles in Broadway productions, in 1949 he became a [[character actor]] on television. He had a regular role in the hit sitcom ''[[It's a Great Life (TV series)|It's a Great Life]]''  from 1954 to 1956, and guest-starred in dozens of episodes of popular television series from the 1950s through mid-1960s. In 1960, his contributions to film and television were recognized with two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]].\n\n==Early life==\nJames Howard Dunn was born on November 2, 1901, in [[Manhattan]].<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:2WWP-YDZ|title=New York, New York City Births, 1846\u20131909|publisher=[[FamilySearch]]|year=2020|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}</ref> His parents, Ralph H. Dunn (c. 1875\u20131943), a member of the [[New York Stock Exchange]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48495215/the-wilkes-barre-record/|title=Retired Broker Dies|author=Associated Press|newspaper=The Wilkes-Barre Record|date=March 18, 1943|page=20|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> and mother Jessie L. Archer (c. 1871\u20131946)<ref name=jesse/> had married in January 1901.<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:24SX-JT7 |title=Ralph Dunn|publisher=Family Search|year=2020|accessdate=April 12, 2020}}</ref> He was their only child.<ref name=jesse/> He was of Irish descent.{{sfn|Griffin|1980|p=319}}<ref name=deseret/> \n\nWhile wintering with his parents at [[Shippan Point]], Connecticut, the four-year-old Dunn had a near-accident reported in ''[[The New York Times]]''. While seated in a pony-drawn cart with his babysitter, the girl's pet bulldog came out and lunged at him. It missed the cart and landed at the feet of the pony, which kicked it. The dog then attacked the pony. The wounded pony bolted, overturning the cart. Dunn and the girl were thrown clear and the dog rushed at Dunn again, but the girl protected him and bystanders drove the dog away. The pair was unhurt.<ref name=dog>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48496331/the-new-york-times/|title=Dog Attacks Pony and Boy|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|date=December 29, 1905|page=9|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\nDunn grew up in [[New Rochelle, New York]], and attended school there.<ref name=lansing/> He often skipped high school classes to hang around film studios in [[The Bronx|the upper Bronx]].<ref name=upi/>\n\n==Early film and stage career==\nAfter graduation, Dunn tried his hand at sales, selling [[Food truck|lunch wagons]] and also becoming an automobile demonstrator.<ref name=lansing>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48680035/lansing-state-journal/|title=James Dunn is Popular in Hollywood|newspaper=[[Lansing State Journal]]|date=September 5, 1931|page=5| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref><ref name=Miami>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48354889/the-miami-herald/|title=None Of That Love For TV's James Dunn|newspaper=[[Miami Herald|The Miami Herald]]|date=June 3, 1956|page=150|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> He worked for three years in his father's brokerage firm.<ref name=dispatch/> But his real love was the theater.<ref name=nyt/> In 1927 he left his father's employ to join a small theatrical troupe.<ref name=dispatch/> He also found jobs as an extra in [[short film]]s at [[Paramount Pictures]]' [[Long Island]] studios.<ref name=Miami/> He joined a [[Repertory theater|stock theater]] company out of [[Englewood, New Jersey]], for a 37-week engagement, and another stock theater company in [[Winnipeg]], Canada, for a 22-week run.<ref name=dispatch/><ref name=hungry>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48354015/the-winnipeg-tribune/|title=Jimmy Dunn Returns Famous But Hungry|newspaper=[[Winnipeg Tribune|The Winnipeg Tribune]]|date=March 4, 1938|page=3|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Upon his return to New York, he landed the male lead in the 1929 Broadway musical ''[[Sweet Adeline (musical)|Sweet Adeline]]'', opposite [[Helen Morgan]].<ref name=dispatch/>\n\n==Success in Hollywood==\nDunn's Broadway performance attracted the attention of film studio executives.<ref name=nyt/> In 1931, [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]], which conducted its screen tests at [[Fox Film]]'s [[Kaufman Astoria Studios|Astoria Studios]] in Queens, New York, called Dunn in for a screen test. A Fox employee asked if they could also test Dunn, and had him read a scene from the stage production of ''Bad Girl''. While Metro was not impressed with their result, director [[Frank Borzage]] liked Dunn's screen test and wanted to cast him in his upcoming [[Bad Girl (1931 film)|film version of ''Bad Girl'']].<ref name=Detroit>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48351771/detroit-free-press/|title=Casual Test Put Dunn in Films|date=December 30, 1931|newspaper=[[Detroit Free Press]]|page=13|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Dunn signed a film contract with Fox a few days later and relocated to Hollywood.<ref name=nyt/><ref name=Detroit/> His mother came to live with him the following year.<ref name=jesse>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48495700/the-sacramento-bee/|title=Mother Of James Dunn, Film Actor, Succumbs|author=Associated Press|newspaper=[[The Sacramento Bee]]|date=May 31, 1946|page=9|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref><ref name=dispatch/> \n\nDunn made his screen debut in ''[[Bad Girl (1931 film)|Bad Girl]]'' (1931),<ref>{{cite web |url=https://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/moviedetails/7252|title=Bad Girl (1931)|work=AFI Catalog|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|year=2019}}</ref> which catapulted him and co-star [[Sally Eilers]] to \"overnight fame\".<ref name=nyt/> A ''[[The Baltimore Sun|Baltimore Evening Sun]]'' review was typical of the praise lavished on Dunn: \"Without Dunn, ''Bad Girl'' would be just another movie. With him, it's something that provokes chuckles, tears, laughs, sighs and everything else that a nice little movie hopes to provoke\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48680307/the-evening-sun/ |title=For Film Fans|author=Q.E.D.|newspaper=[[The Baltimore Sun|Baltimore Evening Sun]]|page=22|date=September 9, 1931| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> In response to a review that claimed any actor would have succeeded in the \"sure-fire part\", a ''[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]'' reviewer argued:\n<blockquote>It was a role so skillfully conceived and executed, so sympathetically played and so warm and sincere that one's natural inclination is to put the actor in this case above the role rather than the role above the actor. ... Mr. Dunn, on the other hand, created a character. It had a definite form. It breathed life. It had depth and feeling. Not for a moment were you conscious of James Dunn. You were conscious only of Eddie Collins.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48681065/pittsburgh-post-gazette/|title=About James Dunn And His 'Bad Girl'|first=Harold W.|last=Cohen|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Post-Gazette]]|date=October 17, 1931|page=19|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nWithin a year Dunn was considered \"one of the top 10 box office draws\".<ref name=deseret>{{cite news |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48353770/deseret-news/|title=Dunn Hits Top Again Via Brooklyn's 'Tree'|newspaper=[[Deseret News]]|date=March 7, 1945|page=10| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Dunn and Eilers were re-teamed in ''[[Over the Hill (1931 film)|Over the Hill]]'' (1931), ''[[Dance Team (film)|Dance Team]]'' (1932), ''[[Sailor's Luck]]'' (1933), and ''[[Hold Me Tight (1933 film)|Hold Me Tight]]'' (1933).<ref name=dispatch/><ref>{{cite web |url=http://catalog.afi.com/Catalog/MovieDetails/7312|title=Hold Me Tight (1933)|work=AFI Catalog|publisher=[[American Film Institute]]|year=2019|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> Dunn also played the lead in ''[[Sob Sister]]'' (1931), ''[[Society Girl (1932 film)|Society Girl]]'' (1932), and ''[[Hello, Sister!]]'' (1933).<ref name=dispatch/> By the end of 1933, he was being referred to as \"America's boy friend\" due to his success as a romantic lead.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48351972/the-missoulian/|title='Jimmy and Sally' Picture Shows Youngsters' Romance|newspaper=[[Missoulian|The Missoulian]]|date=January 14, 1934|page=19| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\n===Shirley Temple co-star===\nIn 1934, Dunn appeared in seven films for Fox. Three of them were also the first three film appearances of six-year-old [[Shirley Temple]].{{sfn|Shea|2015|p=39}} In ''[[Stand Up and Cheer!]]'', Dunn and Temple played a father and daughter who performed in one song-and-dance sequence.{{sfn|Hall|2010|p=123}}{{sfn|Hammontree|1998|p=34}} Rather than learn a new routine, Temple was asked to teach Dunn the steps to a tap-dance routine she had already learned in her dancing school.{{sfn|Edwards|2017|p=53}} Their memorable performance prompted studio executives to immediately cast them in a follow-up film, ''[[Baby Take a Bow]]'' (the title was the name of Dunn and Temple's song in ''Stand Up and Cheer!''{{sfn|Edwards|2017|p=66}}), a remake of the 1928 silent film ''[[Square Crooks]]''.{{sfn|Kasson|2014|p=80}} Temple again played Dunn's daughter in this hit film.{{sfn|Kasson|2014|pp=80\u201381}}  Their third{{sfn|Kasson|2014|p=83}} film pairing was in ''[[Bright Eyes (1934 film)|Bright Eyes]]'', a vehicle specifically written for Temple and co-starring Dunn as a bachelor pilot and friend of Temple's deceased father who seeks to adopt her. Temple sang \"[[On the Good Ship Lollipop]]\" aboard Dunn's character's airplane in this film.<ref name=nyt/>\n\nDunn and Temple worked well together. Temple later said that the day they began shooting their first film \"was the start of my great romance with Jimmy Dunn\".{{sfn|Edwards|2017|pp=53, 66}} Though Temple's career soon eclipsed his, Dunn professed to being one of her biggest fans.{{sfn|Beatty|1935|p=75}} Later that same year, Temple was cast in a small part as Dunn's neighbor in ''[[Change of Heart (1934 film)|Change of Heart]]''.{{sfn|Edwards|2017|p=57}}\n\n==Career decline==\nDuring his five years as a contract player with Fox, Dunn appeared in 30 films.<ref name=town/> In 1935, at the height of his popularity, Dunn broke his studio contract two years before its expiration. He was about to start filming ''The Song and Dance Man'', but the project was shelved due to Fox's merger with [[Twentieth Century Pictures]]. Dunn claimed he was \"dissatisfied with pictures recently given me \u2013 except those with Shirley Temple\".<ref name=breaks/> He was reportedly reimbursed for the remainder of his contract.<ref name=breaks>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48352221/courier-post/|title=James Dunn Breaks Fox Film Contract|author=[[United Press International|United Press]]|date=August 22, 1935|newspaper=[[Courier-Post]]|page=7}}</ref>\n\nWith musicals on the wane in the late 1930s, Dunn's career slumped as he was cast in a series of \"mediocre comedies and melodramas\".{{sfn|Shea|2015|p=39}}<ref name=nyt/> His prospects were also hurt by his growing problem with alcoholism.{{sfn|Shea|2015|p=39}} During the filming of ''[[George White's 1935 Scandals]]'', shooting started in the late morning to accommodate Dunn and other members of the cast who frequently imbibed.{{sfn|Kobal|1985|p=222}}{{sfn|Thomas|1984|p=255}} Dunn began to be regarded as \"unemployable\" by the major studios.<ref name=town>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/21840799/james-dunn/|title=Actor James Dunn Dies at Age 61|author=Associated Press|newspaper=[[The Town Talk]]|date=September 4, 1967|page=23| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> \n\nIn 1940, Dunn returned to Broadway in the hit musical ''[[Panama Hattie]]'' with [[Ethel Merman]], to positive reviews.<ref name=deseret/><ref name=nyt/> \n\n===Academy Award winner===\n[[File:A-Tree-Grows-in-Brooklyn-LIFE-1945.jpg|225px|thumb|Dunn and [[Peggy Ann Garner]] in ''[[A Tree Grows in Brooklyn (1945 film)|A Tree Grows in Brooklyn]]'' (1945)]]\nDunn had not worked in film for five years when he was called in to [[Screen test|screen-test]] for the role of Johnny Nolan, the dreamy alcoholic father in ''[[A Tree Grows in Brooklyn (1945 film)|A Tree Grows in Brooklyn]]'' (1945).<ref name=upi/><ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48787354/the-dispatch/|title=Movies in Review|first=Sophia|last=Kondos|newspaper=Daily Dispatch|date=April 14, 1945|page=10| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Dunn had returned to Hollywood in 1944 to seek film roles but had not applied for this part for fear of another rejection.<ref name=deseret/> But a friend, actress and dancer Gloria Grafton, urged casting directors involved in the extensive talent search to hire him.<ref name=deseret/> Director [[Elia Kazan]] said he chose Dunn for the role because drinking had impacted the actor's career, and because he saw \"a trace of pain in Dunn's face that indicated he had 'failed the test of life' and [Kazan] wanted to bring that 'pain' to the screen\".{{sfn|Bodnar|2006|p=105}} Dunn reportedly drew from his own experiences for his characterization.<ref name=town/>\n\nCritics widely hailed his performance as his \"finest\".<ref name=nyt/> The ''[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]]'' wrote: \"Mr. Dunn's Johnny Nolan has the mark of greatness about it, and he has never done before, nor ever will again, anything of more sublime conviction\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48779293/pittsburgh-sun-telegraph/ |title='Tree' Packs Real Power As Picture|first=Karl|last=Krug|date=March 5, 1945|newspaper=[[Pittsburgh Sun-Telegraph]] | via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> [[Bosley Crowther]] of ''[[The New York Times]]'' commended the strong screen chemistry achieved by Dunn and [[Peggy Ann Garner]], who played his daughter Francie:\n\n<blockquote>Little Miss Garner, with her plain face and lank hair, is Francie Nolan to the life. And James Dunn plays her father, Johnny Nolan, with deep and sympathetic tenderness. In the radiant performance by these two actors of a dreamy adoration between father and child is achieved a pictorial demonstration of emotion that is sublimely eloquent.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1945/03/01/archives/the-screen-in-review-at-the-paramount-at-the-fiftyfifth-street-a.html |title=THE SCREEN IN REVIEW; At the Paramount At the Fifty-fifth Street 'A Tree Grows in Brooklyn,' Film Version of Betty Smith's Novel, With a Uniformly Fine Cast, Opens at the Roxy.|first=Bosley|last=Crowther|authorlink=Bosley Crowther|date=March 1, 1945|accessdate=April 15, 2020|work=The New York Times}}</ref></blockquote>\n\nAt the [[18th Academy Awards]] ceremony, Dunn received the [[Academy Award for Best Supporting Actor]] for his performance.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.oscars.org/oscars/ceremonies/1946|title=The 18th Academy Awards \u2013 1946|publisher=[[Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences]]|year=2019|accessdate=April 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nWinning the Oscar, however, did not revive his film prospects. While Dunn did not raise his price, acting jobs were slow in coming.<ref name=rahn>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48354752/st-louis-globe-democrat/|title=It's a Great Life\u2014This TV Business, Says James Dunn|first=Pete|last=Rahn|date=April 1, 1956|newspaper=[[St. Louis Globe-Democrat]]|page=61|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=83}} He returned to the role of an alcoholic father in ''[[Killer McCoy]]'' (1947) opposite [[Mickey Rooney]], to complimentary reviews.<ref name=nyt/>{{sfn|Romano|2004|p=70}}<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48679472/the-los-angeles-times/|title=Fight Story Spotlights Young Star|first=John L.|last=Scott|date=January 7, 1948|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|page=15|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> His last film performance for nearly a decade was in the short film ''[[A Wonderful Life (1951 film)|A Wonderful Life]]'' (1951), produced for the [[Christian film industry]].{{sfn|Lindvall|Quicke|2011|p=67}} Dunn appeared in four films in the 1960s, including another role as an alcoholic in ''[[The Bramble Bush]]'' (1960).<ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Return to the stage==\nIn 1947, largely on the basis of his performance in ''A Tree Grows in Brooklyn'', Dunn was cast as Jamie Tyrone, a man who resorted to drink to forget his sad past, in [[Eugene O'Neill]]'s semi-autobiographical play ''[[A Moon for the Misbegotten]]''.{{sfn|Shea|2015|p=39}} Considered the \"name\" actor in the production, Dunn was given a run-of-the-play contract and $1,000 per week, compared to the $750 per week salary of fellow performer [[J. M. Kerrigan]].{{sfn|Shea|2015|p=39}}  During rehearsals, O'Neill was dissatisfied with Dunn's portrayal of Tyrone, a character based on O'Neill's brother, claiming that Dunn \"wasn't playing the role with enough gentlemanliness\". The director defended Dunn's interpretation of the script.{{sfn|Gelb|Gelb|2016|p=401}} Meanwhile, Dunn felt out of his league playing tragedy rather than comedy. He had never seen an O'Neill play and said his wife had persuaded him to take the part for the \"prestige\".{{sfn|Shea|2015|pp=40\u201341}} The production budget ballooned by 10% in order to have [[dress rehearsal]]s take place in New York rather than in the first out-of-town [[Tryout (theatre)|tryout]] in [[Columbus, Ohio]], in order to accommodate Dunn's poor health.{{sfn|Shea|2015|p=41}} While Dunn's performance garnered critical praise on the tour,<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48683794/the-windsor-star/|title=The Theatre And Its People|newspaper=[[Windsor Star|The Windsor Star]]|date=March 12, 1947|page=14|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> he left the production before it reached Broadway.<ref name=nyt/>\n\nIn 1948,<ref name=nyt/> Dunn succeeded [[James Stewart]] in ''[[Harvey (play)|Harvey]]'', appearing in 108 performances of the long-running Broadway play.<ref>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48553752/dayton-daily-news/|title=Seven Stage And Movie Stars Have Played In The Title Role of 'Harvey'|newspaper=[[Dayton Daily News]]|date=January 15, 1950|page=29|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> In 1951, Dunn played [[Willy Loman]] in ''[[Death of a Salesman]]'' at the [[Norwich, Connecticut|Norwich]] Summer Theater.<ref name=nyt/>\n\n==Television career==\n[[File:James Dunn.jpg|right|thumb|Dunn in 1955]]\nIn 1949, Dunn pursued a new direction as a [[character actor]] on television.<ref name=rahn/> He guest-starred in dozens of episodes of popular television series in the 1950s through mid-1960s, including ''[[Bonanza]]'', ''[[Rawhide (TV series)|Rawhide]]'', ''[[Route 66 (TV series)|Route 66]]'', ''[[Ben Casey]]'', and ''[[The Virginian (TV series)|The Virginian]]''.<ref name=tvg/>{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=86}} He had a regular role in the popular sitcom ''[[It's a Great Life (TV series)|It's a Great Life]]'', which aired 78 episodes from 1954 to 1956.{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=80}} Dunn played Earl Morgan, the deadbeat brother-in-law of the main character, Amy Morgan ([[Frances Bavier]]), who was always concocting [[get-rich-quick scheme]]s to interest Amy's tenants, Steve Connors ([[William Bishop (actor)|William Bishop]]) and Denny Davis ([[Michael O'Shea (actor)|Michael O'Shea]]). {{sfn|Tucker|2010|pp=81\u201382}} The three male comedians had good rapport and often ad-libbed their lines.<ref name=rahn/>{{sfn|Tucker|2010|p=82}} In 1962, Dunn played a clown in full makeup and costume in an episode of ''[[Follow the Sun (TV series)|Follow the Sun]]'', and sang \"On the Good Ship Lollipop\" from his 1934 film ''Bright Eyes''.<ref name=dailynews>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48804285/philadelphia-daily-news/|title=James Dunn Makes TV Singing Debut|first=Joe|last=Finnigan|agency=UPI|date=March 1, 1962|publisher=[[Philadelphia Daily News]]|page=37|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref>\n\n==Acting style==\nIn his Hollywood heyday in the 1930s, Dunn was noted for his \"clean-cut good lucks and boyish charm\".<ref name=Miami/> As he matured, ''[[The New York Times]]'' described Dunn's \"trademark\" as an \"expression of slightly battered wistfulness\".<ref name=nyt>{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/09/04/archives/james-dunn-actor-dies-at-61-academy-award-winner-in-46-honored-as.html|title=James Dunn, Actor, Dies at 61; Academy Award Winner in '46; Honored as Tippling Father in 'A Tree Grows in Brooklyn' Shirley Temple Co-Star|date=September 4, 1967|accessdate=April 6, 2020|work=[[The New York Times]]}}</ref> The Associated Press characterized Dunn's later film persona as \"a well-meaning type of fellow whom women marry to mother\".<ref name=town/> \n\n==Recognition==\n[[File:James Dunn Hollywood Star.jpg|right|thumb|Star on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] honoring Dunn's contributions to television]]\nDunn was honored with two stars on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]]\u2014one for his contributions to motion pictures at 6555 [[Hollywood Boulevard]], and one for his contributions to television at 7010 Hollywood Boulevard. Both were dedicated on February 8, 1960.<ref>{{cite web |title=James Dunn|url=http://www.walkoffame.com/james-dunn |publisher=Hollywood Walk of Fame |accessdate=14 July 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180714012035/http://www.walkoffame.com/james-dunn |archivedate=14 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nEven after his rise to fame in the 1930s, Dunn was described as \"unaffected and friendly\".<ref name=hungry/> When he was not working, Dunn enjoyed golf and flying his airplane.<ref name=dispatch/><ref name=Othman/> He earned a pilot's license shortly after his arrival in California.<ref name=Miami/>\n\n===Marriages===\nDunn was married three times. His first marriage ended in divorce in 1922.<ref name=marr>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/image/?clipping_id=48538854|title=Actor Dunn Weds Singer|newspaper=[[The Los Angeles Times]]|date=March 8, 1945|page=2|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> In 1938, he married 18-year-old actress [[Frances Gifford]] and starred with her in the low-budget ''[[Mercy Plane]]'' (1939).{{sfn|Maltin|1994|p=331}} The marriage failed in 1942 as his career was in decline and he was struggling with alcoholism;{{sfn|Maltin|1994|p=332}} their divorce was finalized in 1943.<ref name=marr/> In 1945 Dunn married his third wife, singer Edna Rush,<ref name=marr/> who survived him.<ref name=upi/> Dunn adopted Rush's three-and-a-half-year-old son Billy.<ref name=town/>\n\n===Finances===\nIn the 1930s, Dunn's weekly earnings were in the thousands of dollars; he also charged $5,000 for a personal appearance tour. His mother took charge of his finances and invested most of his earnings in stocks, bonds, real estate, and trust funds, giving him a weekly allowance.<ref name=Othman/><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48495611/the-times-news/|title=Mother of Actor James Dunn Dies|newspaper=[[Times-News (Idaho)|Times-News]]|date=May 31, 1946|page=1|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> As a result, after Dunn left Fox and his career slumped, he had financial security. Upon his 1938 marriage, Dunn's mother gave him control of his portfolio.<ref name=Othman>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48353341/pittsburgh-post-gazette/|title=James Dunn Can Thank His Mother|first=Fredrick C.|last=Othman|agency=United Press|newspaper=Pittsburgh Post-Gazette|date=March 1, 1940|page=10|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> Thereafter Dunn lost a $40,000 option on a play, ''Cock of the Walk'', that failed to reach Broadway,<ref name=nyt/>{{sfn|Seaman|1996|p=213\u2013214}} as well as thousands of dollars in the stock market.<ref name=belser/> He was forced to sell his $50,000 house<ref name=hungry/> and move to a two-bedroom apartment in [[Malibu]], from where he commuted to Hollywood.<ref name=belser>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48354514/fort-worth-star-telegram/|title=James Dunn Turning to TV To Try to Recoup Fortune|first=Emily|last=Belser|date=September 12, 1954|newspaper=[[Fort Worth Star-Telegram]]|page=38| via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> \nIn October 1951, he filed for bankruptcy.<ref name=nyt/> However, his mother had reserved one trust fund for him which matured when he turned 50 and paid out $900 per month for life.<ref name=Othman/>\n\n===Death===\nDunn died on September 1, 1967,<ref>{{cite web |url= https://www.familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:VPK5-62C|title=California Death Index, 1940\u20131997|publisher=FamilySearch|year=2020|accessdate=April 13, 2020}}</ref> aged 65, from complications following stomach surgery at [[UCLA Medical Center, Santa Monica|Santa Monica Hospital]].<ref name=upi>{{cite news|url= https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48556137/the-san-bernardino-county-sun/|title=James Dunn, Academy Award Recipient, Dies|date=September 4, 1967|newspaper=[[The San Bernardino Sun]]|page=17|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> His funeral service in [[Santa Monica, California|Santa Monica]] was attended by some 200 people, including fellow actors.<ref name=funeral>{{cite news|url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/48602498/the-bridgeport-post/|title=200 Persons Attend James Dunn Funeral|newspaper=[[Connecticut Post|Bridgeport Post]]|author=Associated Press|date=September 7, 1967|page=43|via=[[Newspapers.com]]}}{{open access}}</ref> His body was cremated and his ashes strewn at sea.<ref name=funeral/>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:James Dunn Janet Gaynor 1934.JPG|thumb|right|Dunn and [[Janet Gaynor]] in ''[[Change of Heart (1934 film)|Change of Heart]]'' (1934)]] \n[[File:Judge Dunn Lawrence Welcome Home.jpg|right|thumb|(L. to r.) [[Arline Judge]], Dunn, and [[Rosina Lawrence]] in ''[[Welcome Home (1935 film)|Welcome Home]]'' (1935)]]\n[[File:That Brennan Girl (1946) still 1.jpg|right|thumb|Dunn and [[Mona Freeman]] in ''[[That Brennan Girl]]'' (1946)]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+Film\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|1929\n|''In the Nick of Time''\n|\n|Short, as Jimmy Dunn\n|-\n|rowspan=4|1930\n|''Believe It or Not''\n|Reporter\n|Short, uncredited\n|-\n|''Barefoot Days''\n|\n|Short\n|-\n|''Tom Thumbs Down''\n|\n|Short, as Jimmy Dunn\n|-\n|''The Varsity Show''\n|\n|Short, as Jimmy Dunn\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1931\n|''[[Bad Girl (1931 film)|Bad Girl]]''\n|Eddie Collins\n|\n|-\n|''[[Sob Sister]]''\n|Garry Webster\n|\n|-\n|''[[Over the Hill (1931 film)|Over the Hill]]''\n|Johnny Shelby (as adult)\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=3|1932\n|''[[Society Girl (film)|Society Girl]]''\n|Johnny Malone\n|\n|-\n|''[[Dance Team (film)|Dance Team]]''\n|Jimmy Mulligan\n|\n|-\n|''[[Handle with Care (1932 film)|Handle with Care]]''\n|Bill Gordon\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=7|1933\n|''[[Hold Me Tight (1933 film)|Hold Me Tight]]''\n|Chuck Evans\n|\n|-\n|''[[Hello, Sister!]]''\n|Jimmy\n|\n|-\n|''[[The Girl in 419]]''\n|Dr. Daniel French\n|\n|-\n|''[[Sailor's Luck]]''\n|Jimmy Fenimore Harrigan\n|\n|-\n|''[[Arizona to Broadway]]''\n|Smiley\n|\n|-\n|''[[Jimmy and Sally]]''\n|Jimmy O'Connor\n|\n|-\n|''[[Take a Chance (1933 film)|Take a Chance]]''\n|Duke Stanley\n|\n|-\n|rowspan=7|1934\n|''[[Baby Take a Bow]]''\n|Eddie Ellison\n|\n|-\n|''[[Have a Heart (film)|Have a Heart]]''\n|Jimmie Flaherty\n|\n|-\n|''[[Bright Eyes (1934 film)|Bright Eyes]]''\n|James 'Loop' Merritt\n|\n|-\n|''[[365 Nights in Hollywood]]''\n|Jimmie Dale\n|\n|-\n|''[[Hold That Girl]]''\n|Barney Sullivan\n|\n|-\